    "plainText": "PRE-ERECTION PLANNING AND SITE READINESS TASK MODULE\n\nVerifying site conditions, support readiness, notifications, access, and sequence before steel erection starts\n\nThis task element supports steel-erection planning, training, and field execution for review of erection drawings, access and storage preparation, concrete and anchor-rod verification, crane support evaluation, laydown planning, utility awareness, and sequence review. It focuses on the practical steps needed to perform the task safely and hand it off cleanly to the next crew.\n\n1. Task Scope & Work Conditions\n\n1.1 Task purpose  This task covers review of erection drawings, access and storage preparation, concrete and anchor-rod verification, crane support evaluation, laydown planning, utility awareness, and sequence review. The work should be sequenced so that later tasks inherit a safe starting condition rather than a partially controlled one.\n\n1.2 Main exposure profile  The main exposures during this task are unsafe lifting, misfit bases, unstable routes, overhead utility conflict, and unauthorized sequence changes caused by poor preparation. These exposures should be treated as part of the task itself, not as side issues.\n\n2. Pre-Task & Pre-Construction Planning\n\n2.1 Planning focus  The planning review should address written concrete-strength notification, anchor-rod notices, access, storage, hoisting routes, weather, first lifts, crane setup, and shutdown criteria. The review should also confirm the communication path for changing conditions or stopping work.\n\n2.2 Daily startup review  The daily review should identify manpower, weather, equipment readiness, adjacent-trade conflict, route restrictions, and any unresolved conditions carried over from the prior shift.\n\n3. Required Equipment and Access\n\n3.1 Core equipment  Typical equipment includes drawings, anchor-bolt information, measuring tools, level or laser tools, radios, weather information, and support details for crane setup or access preparation. The equipment should be placed so the crew does not create extra exposure by chasing tools or material during the task.\n\n3.2 Access and support  Access should be stable, clearly defined, and matched to the exact point where the work is performed so crews are not forced into improvised positions.\n\n4. Hazards & Controls\n\n4.1 Main hazards  The key hazards in this task are unsafe lifting, misfit bases, unstable routes, overhead utility conflict, and unauthorized sequence changes caused by poor preparation. The crew should know which condition is most likely to change first if the work begins to drift away from the plan.\n\n4.2 Primary controls  Primary controls for the task include documented verification, competent inspection, route preparation, clear staging, early defect escalation, and refusal to start from assumptions alone. Controls should be visible to the crew before the active work starts.\n\n5. Structural Stability / Sequence Controls\n\n5.1 Stability link  The structural-stability issue tied to this task is that the sequence must identify where temporary bracing is needed and when each zone is ready for the next task. The sequence should keep the frame in a safe condition before handing the area to the next step.\n\n5.2 Load and access limits  No material, follow-on task, or personnel access should be introduced until the task has actually produced the stable condition assumed by the next crew.\n\n6. Training & Qualification Requirements\n\n6.1 Required knowledge  Workers assigned to this task should understand supervisors and lead workers should understand steel-erection sequencing, lifting-path planning, fall-protection implications, and the technical review path for changing conditions. Training should be role-specific rather than generic.\n\n6.2 Oversight roles  Competent and qualified roles should be identified before the task starts so inspection, approval, and stop-work authority stay clear throughout the operation.\n\n7. Permit / Approval Triggers\n\n7.1 Typical approvals  This task may require written notifications tied to concrete strength and anchor-rod status, plus any site crane, traffic, or temporary-power approvals. Site rules may add approvals beyond the minimum OSHA-required documentation.\n\n7.2 Deviation handling  If field conditions force a change in the planned method, the change should be reviewed and documented through the project path instead of being normalized as a field shortcut.\n\n8. Inspection, Acceptance, and Closeout\n\n8.1 Completion standard  The task is complete when the site is ready for safe unloading and the first lift, and the field condition matches the reviewed documents. Completion should be defined by field condition, not by how much of the shift is left.\n\n8.2 Handoff to the next operation  The handoff should clearly identify what is done, what remains restricted, and what the next crew may safely assume about the area.\n\n9. Additional Related Information\n\n9.1 Practical use  This task element should be used at the pre-task meeting and again when the work area, sequence, or crew changes materially.\n\n9.2 Recordkeeping and communication  A clean handoff supported by clear documentation prevents the next crew from inheriting hidden restrictions or unsafe assumptions.\n\nREFERENCE LANGUAGE AND OSHA SOURCE POINTS\n\nThe inline markers below correspond to the requirement language referenced in the body of this document.\n\nR1. Steel erection begins only after written notification that the concrete in footings, piers, walls, or masonry piers or walls has attained the strength to support erection loads. OSHA 1926.752(a)(1).\n\nR2. The controlling contractor must provide the steel erector written notification of repairs, replacements, or field modifications to anchor rods before column erection. OSHA 1926.752(a)(2) and 1926.755(b).\n\nR3. The controlling contractor must ensure adequate access roads, site conditions, and storage areas for safe steel erection. OSHA 1926.752(c).\n\nR4. Hoisting operations must be pre-planned to reduce employee exposure to overhead loads. OSHA 1926.752(d).\n\nR5. A competent person must perform a pre-shift visual inspection of cranes used in steel erection, and a qualified rigger must inspect rigging prior to each shift. OSHA 1926.753(c).\n\nR6. Structural stability must be maintained at all times during the erection process. OSHA 1926.754(a).\n\nR13. Special training is required for all employees exposed to fall hazards and for connectors, controlled decking zone workers, and workers rigging multiple lifts. OSHA 1926.761(c).\n\nR14. Employers must initiate and maintain accident prevention programs and provide frequent and regular inspections by competent persons. OSHA 1926.20(b)(1)-(2).\n\nR15. The employer shall instruct each employee in the recognition and avoidance of unsafe conditions and the regulations applicable to the work environment. OSHA 1926.21(b)(2).\n\nR16. Debris must be kept cleared from work areas, passageways, and stairs, and waste handled at regular intervals. OSHA 1926.25(a)-(c).",
