    "plainText": "RECEIVING, UNLOADING, INSPECTING, AND STAGING STEEL MODULE\n\nMaterial delivery, shakeout, laydown order, site inspection, and preparation of steel for safe erection\n\nThis task element supports steel-erection planning, training, and field execution for delivery routing, unloading, shipment checking, damage inspection, member identification, protection of components, and staging in erection order. It focuses on the practical steps needed to perform the task safely and hand it off cleanly to the next crew.\n\n1. Task Scope & Work Conditions\n\n1.1 Task purpose  This task covers delivery routing, unloading, shipment checking, damage inspection, member identification, protection of components, and staging in erection order. The work should be sequenced so that later tasks inherit a safe starting condition rather than a partially controlled one.\n\n1.2 Main exposure profile  The main exposures during this task are suspended-load movement, crush points around trucks and cranes, poor laydown support, shifted loads, and rehandling exposure caused by bad staging. These exposures should be treated as part of the task itself, not as side issues.\n\n2. Pre-Task & Pre-Construction Planning\n\n2.1 Planning focus  The planning review should address vehicle approach, crane position, unloading path, laydown locations, slab or ground limits, utility clearance, and inspection method for shortages or damage. The review should also confirm the communication path for changing conditions or stopping work.\n\n2.2 Daily startup review  The daily review should identify manpower, weather, equipment readiness, adjacent-trade conflict, route restrictions, and any unresolved conditions carried over from the prior shift.\n\n3. Required Equipment and Access\n\n3.1 Core equipment  Typical equipment includes lifting equipment, approved rigging, tag lines, dunnage, radios, inspection paperwork, and access-control devices for the unloading zone. The equipment should be placed so the crew does not create extra exposure by chasing tools or material during the task.\n\n3.2 Access and support  Access should be stable, clearly defined, and matched to the exact point where the work is performed so crews are not forced into improvised positions.\n\n4. Hazards & Controls\n\n4.1 Main hazards  The key hazards in this task are suspended-load movement, crush points around trucks and cranes, poor laydown support, shifted loads, and rehandling exposure caused by bad staging. The crew should know which condition is most likely to change first if the work begins to drift away from the plan.\n\n4.2 Primary controls  Primary controls for the task include pre-positioned blocking, controlled hook-up, exclusion zones, clear communication, immediate damage reporting, and staging by erection sequence rather than convenience. Controls should be visible to the crew before the active work starts.\n\n5. Structural Stability / Sequence Controls\n\n5.1 Stability link  The structural-stability issue tied to this task is that members should be stored so they do not roll, twist, pool water, or damage connection material before they are raised. The sequence should keep the frame in a safe condition before handing the area to the next step.\n\n5.2 Load and access limits  No material, follow-on task, or personnel access should be introduced until the task has actually produced the stable condition assumed by the next crew.\n\n6. Training & Qualification Requirements\n\n6.1 Required knowledge  Workers assigned to this task should understand workers should recognize shifted loads, safe hook-up and release, mark identification, and the difference between normal field dirt and actual structural damage. Training should be role-specific rather than generic.\n\n6.2 Oversight roles  Competent and qualified roles should be identified before the task starts so inspection, approval, and stop-work authority stay clear throughout the operation.\n\n7. Permit / Approval Triggers\n\n7.1 Typical approvals  This task may require traffic-control, road-use, or site-access approvals when unloading affects shared routes or occupied facilities. Site rules may add approvals beyond the minimum OSHA-required documentation.\n\n7.2 Deviation handling  If field conditions force a change in the planned method, the change should be reviewed and documented through the project path instead of being normalized as a field shortcut.\n\n8. Inspection, Acceptance, and Closeout\n\n8.1 Completion standard  The task is complete when the shipment is checked, damaged items separated, required parts staged in order, and the unloading area is left organized for the raising crew. Completion should be defined by field condition, not by how much of the shift is left.\n\n8.2 Handoff to the next operation  The handoff should clearly identify what is done, what remains restricted, and what the next crew may safely assume about the area.\n\n9. Additional Related Information\n\n9.1 Practical use  This task element should be used at the pre-task meeting and again when the work area, sequence, or crew changes materially.\n\n9.2 Recordkeeping and communication  A clean handoff supported by clear documentation prevents the next crew from inheriting hidden restrictions or unsafe assumptions.\n\nREFERENCE LANGUAGE AND OSHA SOURCE POINTS\n\nThe inline markers below correspond to the requirement language referenced in the body of this document.\n\nR3. The controlling contractor must ensure adequate access roads, site conditions, and storage areas for safe steel erection. OSHA 1926.752(c).\n\nR4. Hoisting operations must be pre-planned to reduce employee exposure to overhead loads. OSHA 1926.752(d).\n\nR5. A competent person must perform a pre-shift visual inspection of cranes used in steel erection, and a qualified rigger must inspect rigging prior to each shift. OSHA 1926.753(c).\n\nR12. Falling object protection is required where tools, equipment, or materials could strike employees below. OSHA 1926.759.\n\nR14. Employers must initiate and maintain accident prevention programs and provide frequent and regular inspections by competent persons. OSHA 1926.20(b)(1)-(2).\n\nR15. The employer shall instruct each employee in the recognition and avoidance of unsafe conditions and the regulations applicable to the work environment. OSHA 1926.21(b)(2).\n\nR16. Debris must be kept cleared from work areas, passageways, and stairs, and waste handled at regular intervals. OSHA 1926.25(a)-(c).\n\nR18. Rigging equipment used for material handling must be selected, inspected, and used so that it is not damaged or overloaded. OSHA 1926.251.",
