    "plainText": "SETTING COLUMNS AND BASE LINES TASK MODULE\n\nColumn picks, base-plate landing, anchorage checks, plumbing, and early frame restraint\n\nThis task element supports steel-erection planning, training, and field execution for rigging the column, raising it, landing it on the prepared base, engaging the anchor-rod system, initial tightening, plumbing actions, and preparing the line for the next steel. It focuses on the practical steps needed to perform the task safely and hand it off cleanly to the next crew.\n\n1. Task Scope & Work Conditions\n\n1.1 Task purpose  This task covers rigging the column, raising it, landing it on the prepared base, engaging the anchor-rod system, initial tightening, plumbing actions, and preparing the line for the next steel. The work should be sequenced so that later tasks inherit a safe starting condition rather than a partially controlled one.\n\n1.2 Main exposure profile  The main exposures during this task are suspended-load movement, base misalignment, anchor-rod damage, pinch points at landing, and early collapse if the column is released too soon. These exposures should be treated as part of the task itself, not as side issues.\n\n2. Pre-Task & Pre-Construction Planning\n\n2.1 Planning focus  The planning review should address base verification, anchor-rod condition, hardware, elevation, shim or leveling method, and the release condition for each column line. The review should also confirm the communication path for changing conditions or stopping work.\n\n2.2 Daily startup review  The daily review should identify manpower, weather, equipment readiness, adjacent-trade conflict, route restrictions, and any unresolved conditions carried over from the prior shift.\n\n3. Required Equipment and Access\n\n3.1 Core equipment  Typical equipment includes crane, approved rigging, tag lines, leveling tools, spud wrenches, nuts and washers, drift pins as appropriate, plumbing equipment, and radios. The equipment should be placed so the crew does not create extra exposure by chasing tools or material during the task.\n\n3.2 Access and support  Access should be stable, clearly defined, and matched to the exact point where the work is performed so crews are not forced into improvised positions.\n\n4. Hazards & Controls\n\n4.1 Main hazards  The key hazards in this task are suspended-load movement, base misalignment, anchor-rod damage, pinch points at landing, and early collapse if the column is released too soon. The crew should know which condition is most likely to change first if the work begins to drift away from the plan.\n\n4.2 Primary controls  Primary controls for the task include controlled landing, clear body position, no unauthorized anchor correction, and no crane release until the required stable condition is achieved. Controls should be visible to the crew before the active work starts.\n\n5. Structural Stability / Sequence Controls\n\n5.1 Stability link  The structural-stability issue tied to this task is that columns need proper anchorage and temporary restraint before additional members are added. The sequence should keep the frame in a safe condition before handing the area to the next step.\n\n5.2 Load and access limits  No material, follow-on task, or personnel access should be introduced until the task has actually produced the stable condition assumed by the next crew.\n\n6. Training & Qualification Requirements\n\n6.1 Required knowledge  Workers assigned to this task should understand workers should understand landing hazards, anchor-rod sensitivity, base inspection limits, and the proper escalation path for misfit bases. Training should be role-specific rather than generic.\n\n6.2 Oversight roles  Competent and qualified roles should be identified before the task starts so inspection, approval, and stop-work authority stay clear throughout the operation.\n\n7. Permit / Approval Triggers\n\n7.1 Typical approvals  This task may require written concrete-strength notice, anchor-rod modification notice, and any technical review required for base deviations. Site rules may add approvals beyond the minimum OSHA-required documentation.\n\n7.2 Deviation handling  If field conditions force a change in the planned method, the change should be reviewed and documented through the project path instead of being normalized as a field shortcut.\n\n8. Inspection, Acceptance, and Closeout\n\n8.1 Completion standard  The task is complete when the column line is landed, secured for that stage, and clearly handed off for the next framing step. Completion should be defined by field condition, not by how much of the shift is left.\n\n8.2 Handoff to the next operation  The handoff should clearly identify what is done, what remains restricted, and what the next crew may safely assume about the area.\n\n9. Additional Related Information\n\n9.1 Practical use  This task element should be used at the pre-task meeting and again when the work area, sequence, or crew changes materially.\n\n9.2 Recordkeeping and communication  A clean handoff supported by clear documentation prevents the next crew from inheriting hidden restrictions or unsafe assumptions.\n\nREFERENCE LANGUAGE AND OSHA SOURCE POINTS\n\nThe inline markers below correspond to the requirement language referenced in the body of this document.\n\nR1. Steel erection begins only after written notification that the concrete in footings, piers, walls, or masonry piers or walls has attained the strength to support erection loads. OSHA 1926.752(a)(1).\n\nR2. The controlling contractor must provide the steel erector written notification of repairs, replacements, or field modifications to anchor rods before column erection. OSHA 1926.752(a)(2) and 1926.755(b).\n\nR3. The controlling contractor must ensure adequate access roads, site conditions, and storage areas for safe steel erection. OSHA 1926.752(c).\n\nR5. A competent person must perform a pre-shift visual inspection of cranes used in steel erection, and a qualified rigger must inspect rigging prior to each shift. OSHA 1926.753(c).\n\nR6. Structural stability must be maintained at all times during the erection process. OSHA 1926.754(a).\n\nR7. Columns must be anchored by a minimum of four anchor rods. OSHA 1926.755(a)(1).\n\nR14. Employers must initiate and maintain accident prevention programs and provide frequent and regular inspections by competent persons. OSHA 1926.20(b)(1)-(2).\n\nR15. The employer shall instruct each employee in the recognition and avoidance of unsafe conditions and the regulations applicable to the work environment. OSHA 1926.21(b)(2).",
