    "plainText": "HOISTING AND RIGGING / MULTIPLE LIFT TASK MODULE\n\nStandard picks, controlled load paths, and multiple-lift procedures for structural steel members\n\nThis task element supports steel-erection planning, training, and field execution for rigging the member or members, making the pick, moving the load along the planned path, controlling swing and rotation, and landing the steel for connection or staged placement. It focuses on the practical steps needed to perform the task safely and hand it off cleanly to the next crew.\n\n1. Task Scope & Work Conditions\n\n1.1 Task purpose  This task covers rigging the member or members, making the pick, moving the load along the planned path, controlling swing and rotation, and landing the steel for connection or staged placement. The work should be sequenced so that later tasks inherit a safe starting condition rather than a partially controlled one.\n\n1.2 Main exposure profile  The main exposures during this task are rigging failure, uncontrolled rotation, personnel under loads, utility contact, and confusion during multiple-lift separation at the receiving end. These exposures should be treated as part of the task itself, not as side issues.\n\n2. Pre-Task & Pre-Construction Planning\n\n2.1 Planning focus  The planning review should address load weight, center of gravity, rigging method, route, landing condition, weather, communication method, and whether the lift is special, critical, or multiple-lift work. The review should also confirm the communication path for changing conditions or stopping work.\n\n2.2 Daily startup review  The daily review should identify manpower, weather, equipment readiness, adjacent-trade conflict, route restrictions, and any unresolved conditions carried over from the prior shift.\n\n3. Required Equipment and Access\n\n3.1 Core equipment  Typical equipment includes slings, shackles, chokers, spreaders where needed, tag lines, certified multiple-lift assemblies where used, radios, load charts, and barricades for the route. The equipment should be placed so the crew does not create extra exposure by chasing tools or material during the task.\n\n3.2 Access and support  Access should be stable, clearly defined, and matched to the exact point where the work is performed so crews are not forced into improvised positions.\n\n4. Hazards & Controls\n\n4.1 Main hazards  The key hazards in this task are rigging failure, uncontrolled rotation, personnel under loads, utility contact, and confusion during multiple-lift separation at the receiving end. The crew should know which condition is most likely to change first if the work begins to drift away from the plan.\n\n4.2 Primary controls  Primary controls for the task include pre-planned routes, pre-shift inspections, qualified-rigger involvement, exclusion zones, clear stop-work authority, and disciplined separation of personnel from the load path. Controls should be visible to the crew before the active work starts.\n\n5. Structural Stability / Sequence Controls\n\n5.1 Stability link  The structural-stability issue tied to this task is that the receiving condition has to be ready before the lift arrives; the hook should not outpace the structure. The sequence should keep the frame in a safe condition before handing the area to the next step.\n\n5.2 Load and access limits  No material, follow-on task, or personnel access should be introduced until the task has actually produced the stable condition assumed by the next crew.\n\n6. Training & Qualification Requirements\n\n6.1 Required knowledge  Workers assigned to this task should understand workers should understand their role, the load path, signal protocol, route restrictions, and the training requirements for multiple-lift work. Training should be role-specific rather than generic.\n\n6.2 Oversight roles  Competent and qualified roles should be identified before the task starts so inspection, approval, and stop-work authority stay clear throughout the operation.\n\n7. Permit / Approval Triggers\n\n7.1 Typical approvals  This task may require lift permits, critical-lift approvals, utility coordination, and other site-controlled authorizations for higher-risk picks. Site rules may add approvals beyond the minimum OSHA-required documentation.\n\n7.2 Deviation handling  If field conditions force a change in the planned method, the change should be reviewed and documented through the project path instead of being normalized as a field shortcut.\n\n8. Inspection, Acceptance, and Closeout\n\n8.1 Completion standard  The task is complete when the load is landed safely, the receiving crew has control, and no unresolved exposure remains in the route or landing area. Completion should be defined by field condition, not by how much of the shift is left.\n\n8.2 Handoff to the next operation  The handoff should clearly identify what is done, what remains restricted, and what the next crew may safely assume about the area.\n\n9. Additional Related Information\n\n9.1 Practical use  This task element should be used at the pre-task meeting and again when the work area, sequence, or crew changes materially.\n\n9.2 Recordkeeping and communication  A clean handoff supported by clear documentation prevents the next crew from inheriting hidden restrictions or unsafe assumptions.\n\nREFERENCE LANGUAGE AND OSHA SOURCE POINTS\n\nThe inline markers below correspond to the requirement language referenced in the body of this document.\n\nR3. The controlling contractor must ensure adequate access roads, site conditions, and storage areas for safe steel erection. OSHA 1926.752(c).\n\nR4. Hoisting operations must be pre-planned to reduce employee exposure to overhead loads. OSHA 1926.752(d).\n\nR5. A competent person must perform a pre-shift visual inspection of cranes used in steel erection, and a qualified rigger must inspect rigging prior to each shift. OSHA 1926.753(c).\n\nR12. Falling object protection is required where tools, equipment, or materials could strike employees below. OSHA 1926.759.\n\nR13. Special training is required for all employees exposed to fall hazards and for connectors, controlled decking zone workers, and workers rigging multiple lifts. OSHA 1926.761(c).\n\nR18. Rigging equipment used for material handling must be selected, inspected, and used so that it is not damaged or overloaded. OSHA 1926.251.",
