    "plainText": "INSTALLING OPEN WEB STEEL JOISTS AND BRIDGING TASK MODULE\n\nPlacing joists, making seat connections, stabilizing the line, and preparing for deck work\n\nThis task element supports steel-erection planning, training, and field execution for hoisting joists, guiding them into the seat, installing the required field bolts, following the stabilizing and bridging sequence, and preparing the line for later deck activity. It focuses on the practical steps needed to perform the task safely and hand it off cleanly to the next crew.\n\n1. Task Scope & Work Conditions\n\n1.1 Task purpose  This task covers hoisting joists, guiding them into the seat, installing the required field bolts, following the stabilizing and bridging sequence, and preparing the line for later deck activity. The work should be sequenced so that later tasks inherit a safe starting condition rather than a partially controlled one.\n\n1.2 Main exposure profile  The main exposures during this task are fall hazards during receiving work, joist roll or collapse, pinch points at the seat, and premature loading of an unready joist line. These exposures should be treated as part of the task itself, not as side issues.\n\n2. Pre-Task & Pre-Construction Planning\n\n2.1 Planning focus  The planning review should address joist details, spans, column-line conditions, required bridging or stabilizer details, and the point where deck or bundle loading may begin. The review should also confirm the communication path for changing conditions or stopping work.\n\n2.2 Daily startup review  The daily review should identify manpower, weather, equipment readiness, adjacent-trade conflict, route restrictions, and any unresolved conditions carried over from the prior shift.\n\n3. Required Equipment and Access\n\n3.1 Core equipment  Typical equipment includes approved rigging, tag lines, joist bolts, bridging materials, access equipment, communication devices, and fall protection for the receiving crew. The equipment should be placed so the crew does not create extra exposure by chasing tools or material during the task.\n\n3.2 Access and support  Access should be stable, clearly defined, and matched to the exact point where the work is performed so crews are not forced into improvised positions.\n\n4. Hazards & Controls\n\n4.1 Main hazards  The key hazards in this task are fall hazards during receiving work, joist roll or collapse, pinch points at the seat, and premature loading of an unready joist line. The crew should know which condition is most likely to change first if the work begins to drift away from the plan.\n\n4.2 Primary controls  Primary controls for the task include safe receiving positions, field bolting at each end of the bottom chord before release, bridging in sequence, and withholding load until the line is accepted. Controls should be visible to the crew before the active work starts.\n\n5. Structural Stability / Sequence Controls\n\n5.1 Stability link  The structural-stability issue tied to this task is that joist work depends on field bolting and bridging sequence as the structural protection. The sequence should keep the frame in a safe condition before handing the area to the next step.\n\n5.2 Load and access limits  No material, follow-on task, or personnel access should be introduced until the task has actually produced the stable condition assumed by the next crew.\n\n6. Training & Qualification Requirements\n\n6.1 Required knowledge  Workers assigned to this task should understand workers should understand the joist release rule, bridging expectations, and why premature loading is a collapse hazard. Training should be role-specific rather than generic.\n\n6.2 Oversight roles  Competent and qualified roles should be identified before the task starts so inspection, approval, and stop-work authority stay clear throughout the operation.\n\n7. Permit / Approval Triggers\n\n7.1 Typical approvals  This task may require technical review for unusual joist conditions, damaged joists, altered bridging, or project-specific changes to the joist sequence. Site rules may add approvals beyond the minimum OSHA-required documentation.\n\n7.2 Deviation handling  If field conditions force a change in the planned method, the change should be reviewed and documented through the project path instead of being normalized as a field shortcut.\n\n8. Inspection, Acceptance, and Closeout\n\n8.1 Completion standard  The task is complete when the joists are placed, the required field bolts are installed, the stabilization steps for that phase are complete, and the handoff to decking is clear. Completion should be defined by field condition, not by how much of the shift is left.\n\n8.2 Handoff to the next operation  The handoff should clearly identify what is done, what remains restricted, and what the next crew may safely assume about the area.\n\n9. Additional Related Information\n\n9.1 Practical use  This task element should be used at the pre-task meeting and again when the work area, sequence, or crew changes materially.\n\n9.2 Recordkeeping and communication  A clean handoff supported by clear documentation prevents the next crew from inheriting hidden restrictions or unsafe assumptions.\n\nREFERENCE LANGUAGE AND OSHA SOURCE POINTS\n\nThe inline markers below correspond to the requirement language referenced in the body of this document.\n\nR5. A competent person must perform a pre-shift visual inspection of cranes used in steel erection, and a qualified rigger must inspect rigging prior to each shift. OSHA 1926.753(c).\n\nR9. Open web joists must be field-bolted at each end of the bottom chord before release from the hoisting line. OSHA 1926.757(a)(1)(iii).\n\nR11. Employees exposed to unprotected sides or edges in steel erection must be protected in accordance with the steel erection fall protection rules, including connector and controlled decking zone provisions. OSHA 1926.760(a)-(c).\n\nR12. Falling object protection is required where tools, equipment, or materials could strike employees below. OSHA 1926.759.\n\nR13. Special training is required for all employees exposed to fall hazards and for connectors, controlled decking zone workers, and workers rigging multiple lifts. OSHA 1926.761(c).\n\nR15. The employer shall instruct each employee in the recognition and avoidance of unsafe conditions and the regulations applicable to the work environment. OSHA 1926.21(b)(2).",
