    "plainText": "INSTALLING METAL DECKING AND CONTROLLING OPENINGS TASK MODULE\n\nLanding deck bundles, spreading deck, securing sheets, and controlling leading edges and openings\n\nThis task element supports steel-erection planning, training, and field execution for landing deck bundles in approved locations, spreading and laying deck tightly, securing the deck, controlling holes and penetrations, and restricting access near leading edges. It focuses on the practical steps needed to perform the task safely and hand it off cleanly to the next crew.\n\n1. Task Scope & Work Conditions\n\n1.1 Task purpose  This task covers landing deck bundles in approved locations, spreading and laying deck tightly, securing the deck, controlling holes and penetrations, and restricting access near leading edges. The work should be sequenced so that later tasks inherit a safe starting condition rather than a partially controlled one.\n\n1.2 Main exposure profile  The main exposures during this task are fall hazards at deck edges and openings, bundle-loading mistakes, dropped objects below, and incomplete walking surfaces during rapid deck progression. These exposures should be treated as part of the task itself, not as side issues.\n\n2. Pre-Task & Pre-Construction Planning\n\n2.1 Planning focus  The planning review should address bundle landing points, spread order, opening locations, controlled decking zone boundaries where used, fall-protection method, and access restrictions below. The review should also confirm the communication path for changing conditions or stopping work.\n\n2.2 Daily startup review  The daily review should identify manpower, weather, equipment readiness, adjacent-trade conflict, route restrictions, and any unresolved conditions carried over from the prior shift.\n\n3. Required Equipment and Access\n\n3.1 Core equipment  Typical equipment includes hoisting gear for deck bundles, fasteners and installation tools, radios, barricade materials, covers or edge controls, and fall protection suited to the work method. The equipment should be placed so the crew does not create extra exposure by chasing tools or material during the task.\n\n3.2 Access and support  Access should be stable, clearly defined, and matched to the exact point where the work is performed so crews are not forced into improvised positions.\n\n4. Hazards & Controls\n\n4.1 Main hazards  The key hazards in this task are fall hazards at deck edges and openings, bundle-loading mistakes, dropped objects below, and incomplete walking surfaces during rapid deck progression. The crew should know which condition is most likely to change first if the work begins to drift away from the plan.\n\n4.2 Primary controls  Primary controls for the task include bundles landed only in approved locations, deck laid tight and secured, controlled areas clearly marked, openings managed immediately, and access limited to the active deck crew. Controls should be visible to the crew before the active work starts.\n\n5. Structural Stability / Sequence Controls\n\n5.1 Stability link  The structural-stability issue tied to this task is that deck work only proceeds where the supporting steel is ready for the intended movement and loading. The sequence should keep the frame in a safe condition before handing the area to the next step.\n\n5.2 Load and access limits  No material, follow-on task, or personnel access should be introduced until the task has actually produced the stable condition assumed by the next crew.\n\n6. Training & Qualification Requirements\n\n6.1 Required knowledge  Workers assigned to this task should understand workers should understand the difference between a landed bundle, a spread area, a secured deck surface, and a released walking or working surface. Training should be role-specific rather than generic.\n\n6.2 Oversight roles  Competent and qualified roles should be identified before the task starts so inspection, approval, and stop-work authority stay clear throughout the operation.\n\n7. Permit / Approval Triggers\n\n7.1 Typical approvals  This task may require leading-edge release, deck-load approval, or project-specific signoff before follow-on trades enter newly decked areas. Site rules may add approvals beyond the minimum OSHA-required documentation.\n\n7.2 Deviation handling  If field conditions force a change in the planned method, the change should be reviewed and documented through the project path instead of being normalized as a field shortcut.\n\n8. Inspection, Acceptance, and Closeout\n\n8.1 Completion standard  The task is complete when the deck in that zone is laid tight, secured as required, openings and edges are controlled, and the status of the area is clearly communicated. Completion should be defined by field condition, not by how much of the shift is left.\n\n8.2 Handoff to the next operation  The handoff should clearly identify what is done, what remains restricted, and what the next crew may safely assume about the area.\n\n9. Additional Related Information\n\n9.1 Practical use  This task element should be used at the pre-task meeting and again when the work area, sequence, or crew changes materially.\n\n9.2 Recordkeeping and communication  A clean handoff supported by clear documentation prevents the next crew from inheriting hidden restrictions or unsafe assumptions.\n\nREFERENCE LANGUAGE AND OSHA SOURCE POINTS\n\nThe inline markers below correspond to the requirement language referenced in the body of this document.\n\nR10. Decking must be laid tightly and secured, and controlled decking zones must be clearly marked with restricted access. OSHA 1926.754(e)(5) and 1926.760(c)(2)-(3).\n\nR11. Employees exposed to unprotected sides or edges in steel erection must be protected in accordance with the steel erection fall protection rules, including connector and controlled decking zone provisions. OSHA 1926.760(a)-(c).\n\nR12. Falling object protection is required where tools, equipment, or materials could strike employees below. OSHA 1926.759.\n\nR13. Special training is required for all employees exposed to fall hazards and for connectors, controlled decking zone workers, and workers rigging multiple lifts. OSHA 1926.761(c).",
