    "plainText": "PLUMBING, TEMPORARY BRACING, AND FINAL BOLTING TASK MODULE\n\nAligning the frame, maintaining temporary restraint, and completing bolt-up to the required condition\n\nThis task element supports steel-erection planning, training, and field execution for checking alignment, adjusting the frame to erection tolerances, maintaining or adjusting temporary braces and guys, and completing bolt-up in the required sequence. It focuses on the practical steps needed to perform the task safely and hand it off cleanly to the next crew.\n\n1. Task Scope & Work Conditions\n\n1.1 Task purpose  This task covers checking alignment, adjusting the frame to erection tolerances, maintaining or adjusting temporary braces and guys, and completing bolt-up in the required sequence. The work should be sequenced so that later tasks inherit a safe starting condition rather than a partially controlled one.\n\n1.2 Main exposure profile  The main exposures during this task are fall hazards during adjustment work, stored energy in misaligned connections, movement of partially restrained steel, and removing temporary controls too early. These exposures should be treated as part of the task itself, not as side issues.\n\n2. Pre-Task & Pre-Construction Planning\n\n2.1 Planning focus  The planning review should address which bays are being plumbed, what bracing remains critical, what bolts are still erection bolts versus final bolts, and what other tasks must stay out of the area. The review should also confirm the communication path for changing conditions or stopping work.\n\n2.2 Daily startup review  The daily review should identify manpower, weather, equipment readiness, adjacent-trade conflict, route restrictions, and any unresolved conditions carried over from the prior shift.\n\n3. Required Equipment and Access\n\n3.1 Core equipment  Typical equipment includes turnbuckles, braces, guy lines, levels or transits, wrenches, tightening tools, approved hardware, radios, and access equipment for bolt-up locations. The equipment should be placed so the crew does not create extra exposure by chasing tools or material during the task.\n\n3.2 Access and support  Access should be stable, clearly defined, and matched to the exact point where the work is performed so crews are not forced into improvised positions.\n\n4. Hazards & Controls\n\n4.1 Main hazards  The key hazards in this task are fall hazards during adjustment work, stored energy in misaligned connections, movement of partially restrained steel, and removing temporary controls too early. The crew should know which condition is most likely to change first if the work begins to drift away from the plan.\n\n4.2 Primary controls  Primary controls for the task include step-by-step adjustment, clear communication, temporary restraint maintained until the next safe state, and release decisions made deliberately rather than informally. Controls should be visible to the crew before the active work starts.\n\n5. Structural Stability / Sequence Controls\n\n5.1 Stability link  The structural-stability issue tied to this task is that structural stability remains active during plumbing and bolt-up just as it does during raising. The sequence should keep the frame in a safe condition before handing the area to the next step.\n\n5.2 Load and access limits  No material, follow-on task, or personnel access should be introduced until the task has actually produced the stable condition assumed by the next crew.\n\n6. Training & Qualification Requirements\n\n6.1 Required knowledge  Workers assigned to this task should understand workers should understand alignment goals, tightening procedures, and the difference between normal adjustment and unsafe force on an unstable frame. Training should be role-specific rather than generic.\n\n6.2 Oversight roles  Competent and qualified roles should be identified before the task starts so inspection, approval, and stop-work authority stay clear throughout the operation.\n\n7. Permit / Approval Triggers\n\n7.1 Typical approvals  This task may require technical review for unexpected movement, damaged connection material, field changes to brace configuration, or unusual tightening issues. Site rules may add approvals beyond the minimum OSHA-required documentation.\n\n7.2 Deviation handling  If field conditions force a change in the planned method, the change should be reviewed and documented through the project path instead of being normalized as a field shortcut.\n\n8. Inspection, Acceptance, and Closeout\n\n8.1 Completion standard  The task is complete when the line is aligned to the project requirement, the intended bolt-up condition is achieved for that phase, and remaining braces or restrictions are clearly identified. Completion should be defined by field condition, not by how much of the shift is left.\n\n8.2 Handoff to the next operation  The handoff should clearly identify what is done, what remains restricted, and what the next crew may safely assume about the area.\n\n9. Additional Related Information\n\n9.1 Practical use  This task element should be used at the pre-task meeting and again when the work area, sequence, or crew changes materially.\n\n9.2 Recordkeeping and communication  A clean handoff supported by clear documentation prevents the next crew from inheriting hidden restrictions or unsafe assumptions.\n\nREFERENCE LANGUAGE AND OSHA SOURCE POINTS\n\nThe inline markers below correspond to the requirement language referenced in the body of this document.\n\nR6. Structural stability must be maintained at all times during the erection process. OSHA 1926.754(a).\n\nR12. Falling object protection is required where tools, equipment, or materials could strike employees below. OSHA 1926.759.\n\nR14. Employers must initiate and maintain accident prevention programs and provide frequent and regular inspections by competent persons. OSHA 1926.20(b)(1)-(2).",
